Q fever - UK: FMD carcass disposal 20010701.1256
Date: 1 Jul 2001 17:20:46 +0300
From: Stephen A. Berger, M.D. <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GIDEON <http://www.GideonOnline.com>

Background information on Q fever in the U.K.
---------------------------------------------
Q fever was first reported in the U.K. in 1949.
The mean patient age is 45 years. The male/female ratio is 2.82/1.
Disease rates are highest during the Spring.
7 percent of cases are acquired overseas.
0.6% to 2.8% of sheep are seropositive.
England and Wales reported outbreaks in 1981 (Gwent, 29 cases); and 1983
(Oxfordshire, 25 cases).
1117 cases (1/3 from the southwest region) were reported during 1984 to 1994.
76 cases were confirmed in 1991.
The largest recent outbreak (147 cases) was reported in Birmingham in 1989
-- windborne spread from local farms was implicated.
Northern Ireland reported 443 cases during 1962 to 1989, with highest rates
in County Antrim.
--
Stephen A. Berger, M.D.
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
